{"title_page": "Holiday for Henrietta", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Holiday for Henrietta\n| image          = La_fete_a_henriette_poster.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Julien Duvivier]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Dany Robin]]<br>[[Michel Auclair]]<br>[[Hildegard Knef]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| studio         =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1952}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = France\n| awards         =\n| language       = French\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''Holiday for Henrietta''''' ({{lang-fr|'''La f\u00eate \u00e0 Henriette'''}}) is a 1952 French comedy film directed by [[Julien Duvivier]], and starring [[Dany Robin]], [[Michel Auclair]], and [[Hildegard Knef]].<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/33056</ref> While urgently trying to develop a screenplay for a new film, two screenwriters make it up as they bicker.\n\n''Holiday for Henrietta'' was remade in English as the 1964 film ''[[Paris When It Sizzles]]'', starring [[William Holden]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dany Robin]] as Henriette\n* [[Michel Auclair]] as Marcel\n* [[Hildegard Knef]] as Rita Solar\n* [[Louis Seigner]] as script writer\n* [[Micheline Francey]] as Nicole, script girl\n* [[Henri Cr\u00e9mieux]] as script writer\n* [[Michel Roux]] as Robert\n* [[Daniel Ivernel]] as detective\n* [[Odette Laure]] as Valentine\n* [[Jeannette Batti]] as Gis\u00e8le\n* [[Liliane Maign\u00e9]] as the cigarette girl\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0048104}}\n\n{{Julien Duvivier}}\n\n[[Category:1952 comedy films]]\n[[Category:1952 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Julien Duvivier]]\n[[Category:French comedy films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{1950s-France-film-stub}}\n{{1950s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Holiday for Henrietta\n| image          = La_fete_a_henriette_poster.jpg\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Julien Duvivier]]\n| producer       =\n| writer         =\n| starring       = [[Dany Robin]]<br>[[Michel Auclair]]<br>[[Hildegard Knef]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography =\n| editing        =\n| studio         =\n| distributor    =\n| released       = {{Film date|1952}}\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = France\n| awards         =\n| language       = French\n| budget         =\n}}\n\n'''''Holiday for Henrietta''''' ({{lang-fr|'''La f\u00eate \u00e0 Henriette'''}}) is a 1952 French comedy film directed by [[Julien Duvivier]], and starring [[Dany Robin]], [[Michel Auclair]], and [[Hildegard Knef]].<ref>http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/33056</ref> While urgently trying to develop a screenplay for a new film, two screenwriters make it up as they bicker.\n\n''Holiday for Henrietta'' was remade in English as the 1964 film ''[[Paris When It Sizzles]]'', starring [[William Holden]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]].\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Dany Robin]] as Henriette\n* [[Michel Auclair]] as Marcel\n* [[Hildegard Knef]] as Rita Solar\n* [[Louis Seigner]] as script writer\n* [[Micheline Francey]] as Nicole, script girl\n* [[Henri Cr\u00e9mieux]] as script writer\n* [[Michel Roux]] as Robert\n* [[Daniel Ivernel]] as detective\n* [[Odette Laure]] as Valentine\n* [[Jeannette Batti]] as Gis\u00e8le\n* [[Liliane Maign\u00e9]] as the cigarette girl\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|0048104}}\n\n{{Julien Duvivier}}\n\n[[Category:1950s comedy films]]\n[[Category:1952 films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Julien Duvivier]]\n[[Category:French comedy films]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about screenwriters]]\n\n\n{{1950s-France-film-stub}}\n{{1950s-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BrownHairedGirl", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1950s come