{"title_page": "Frank Crawford", "text_new": "{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Frank Crawford\n| image = Frank Crawford.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1870|3|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1963|11|25|1870|3|12}}\n| death_place = [[Portland, Maine]]\n| alma_mater = \n| coach_years1 = 1891\n| coach_team1 = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n| coach_years2 = 1892\n| coach_team2 = [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]]\n| coach_years3 = 1893\u20131894\n| coach_team3 = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]\n| coach_years4 = 1895\n| coach_team4 = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| coach_years5 = 1896\n| coach_team5 = [[Nebraska Wesleyan Prairie Wolves football|Nebraska Wesleyan]]\n| overall_record = 25\u201314\u20131\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = 1 [[Western Interstate University Football Association|WIUFA]] (1894)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Frank Crawford''' (March 12, 1870 \u2013 November 25, 1963) was a [[college football]] coach, lawyer, and law professor.  He attended [[Yale University]] and served as the first head football coach at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1891.  He also coached at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] (1892), [[Baker University]] (1892), the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] (1893\u20131894), and the [[University of Texas at Austin|University of Texas]] (1895).  He later had a long career as a lawyer in Nebraska and France. He was a professor of law at [[Creighton University School of Law|Creighton College of Law]] from 1906 to 1913.\n\n==Early years==\nCrawford was born in 1870 at [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]].<ref name=TCB/>  He was the son of Francis B. Crawford, a starch manufacturer and state legislator, and Susan J. (Randall) Crawford.<ref>1880 United States Census; Census Place: Colebrook, Coos, New Hampshire; Roll: 762; Family History Film: 1254762; Page: 31A; Enumeration District: 31; Image: 0063.</ref><ref>United States Passport Applications by Frank Crawford dated December 22, 1919 and December 14, 1921 identifies his father as Francis B. Crawford and his date of birth as March 12, 1870 in Colebrook, New Hampshire.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Genealogical and Family History of the State of New Hampshire, vol. 2|page=930|publisher=Lewis Publishing Co.|year=1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cfoI0UIOCKQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  He attended preparatory school at [[St. Johnsbury Academy]] in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont]].<ref name=TCB/>  He enrolled at [[Yale University]], receiving his Bachelor of Arts degree in 1891.  Sources are at odds over whether or not Crawford played football for the [[Yale Bulldogs football]] team.  According to the University of Nebraska web site, Crawford was \"a member of the dominant Yale teams of the mid-1880s.\"<ref name=NEB/>  ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' also reported that Crawford played football at Yale \"for several years.\"<ref name=BENT/>  However, the University of Michigan web site notes that \"Yale archivists found no evidence that he played varsity football\" and concludes that Crawford \"may have played some football while a Bulldog, but definitely did not win a varsity letter.\"<ref name=BENT/>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Michigan===\nAfter graduating from Yale, Crawford enrolled at the [[University of Michigan School of Law]], receiving his law degree in 1893.  As a first-year law student, Crawford was both the unpaid coach and a substitute player for the [[1891 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1891 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1891 Michigan Football Roster|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703111500/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find|archivedate=July 3, 2011}}</ref>  He helped lead the team to a 4\u20135 record.  He has been identified by several sources as the first football coach in University of Michigan history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forum|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 60|year=1954|page=258}}(\"He [Crawford] was the first football coach in University of Michigan history and he was unpaid.\")</ref><ref name=MA08>{{cite news|title=Alumni Meeting in Omaha|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 15|date=December 1908|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgjiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}(\"Frank Crawford first coach of a Michigan football team and captain of the baseball team\")</ref>  Other sources indicate that Crawford and [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]] were the joint head coaches of the 1891 Michigan football team.<ref name=BENT/>  Others state that Murphy relinquished the coaching duties to Crawford midway through the season to allow him to focus on his duties as trainer.<ref name=NEB/>  The ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' reported in November 1891 that the Michigan team was \"coached systematically\" by Murphy, Crawford, [[Horace Greely Prettyman]] and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Players From Ann Arbor: A New but Strong Team Which Will Play a Clean Game|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 14, 1891}}</ref>\n\nWhile attending Michigan, Crawford also played for the [[Michigan Wolverines baseball]] team in 1892 and 1893.  He led the team with a .976 fielding average in 1892.<ref name=MB/>  Crawford appeared in 17 games at catcher and left field for the Wolverines in 1892 and was among the team's leaders in runs (tied for 2nd with 20), stolen bases (tied for 2nd with 13) and putouts (2nd with 115).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Palladium, Vol XXXV|year=1893|page=180|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sSwiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=crawford#v=onepage&q=crawford&f=false}}</ref> He was also selected as the captain of the 1893 baseball team.<ref name=MB>{{cite book|title=The Michigan Book|pages=[https://archive.org/details/michiganbook01michgoog/page/n160 154]\u2013155|publisher=The Inland Press|year=1898|url=https://archive.org/details/michiganbook01michgoog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan Baseball Captains|date=June 5, 2009|publisher=Mgoblue.com|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060509aac.html|access-date=March 5, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714082426/http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060509aac.html|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn his history of the University of Michigan, Wilfred Byron Shaw cites Crawford's hiring as a watershed moment in the history of the school's football program: \"A new era in the history of football at Michigan began in 1891, when with a fair schedule and an experienced coach, Frank Crawford (Yale, '91), '93l, the systematic development of a team began ...\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilfred Byron Shaw|title=The University of Michigan|page=[https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu/page/250 250]|year=1920|publisher=Harcourt, Brace, and Howe|url=https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu}}</ref>  Although football had been played at Michigan without a coaching staff since 1879, the [[Associated Press]] noted at the time of Crawford's death that Crawford \"is credited with introducing football at the University of Michigan in 1891.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Founder of Football At Michigan U. Dies|newspaper=Del-Rio News Herald (AP story)|date=November 26, 1963}}</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nIn 1892, he coached at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] and compiled a 4\u20133 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frank Crawford |publisher=Sports-Reference.com/College Football |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/frank-crawford-1.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105072909/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/frank-crawford-1.html |archivedate=November 5, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1892 Wisconsin Football|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse|url=http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=475&year=1892}}</ref>\n\n===Baker===\nIn November 1892, Crawford served as \"a paid coach-captain player\" for the football team at [[Baker University]] at [[Baldwin, Kansas]].<ref name=sears/>  Crawford reportedly \"brought many innovations,\" including the training table, to Baker's football program.<ref name=sears>{{cite news|author=Hal D. Sears|title=The Moral Threat of Intercollegiate Sports: An 1893 Poll of Ten College Presidents, and the End of \"The Champion Football Team of the Great West\"|publisher=Journal of Sport History, Vol. 19, No. 3|date=Winter 1992|page=215|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1992/JSH1903/jsh1903b.pdf}}</ref>  He led Baker to the Kansas state championship and a 2\u20131 record in \"the triangular league,\" including victories over [[Washburn Ichabods football|Washburn]] (44\u20130) and Kansas (18\u20130).  In December 1892, the ''Leavenworth Times'' reported that Crawford had \"succeeded in instilling sufficient foot ball lore into the western farmers to accomplish the defeat of the University of Kansas team by the Baker eleven last week.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A Tale Unfolded|newspaper=The Daily World (reprinting article from Leavenworth Times)|date=November 27, 1892|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wCtdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7VoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4605,3163149&dq=frank-crawford+%26+baker-university&hl=en}}</ref>  In May 1893, ''The Baker Beacon'' reported: \"The Baker team was ably coached and captained by Frank Crawford who had learned the game at Yale and by the close of the season the team ... was in excellent condition.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Football|date=May 15, 1893|pages=24\u201325|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0iUVAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska===\nIn 1893, Crawford was hired as the head football coach at the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]].  He was the school's first paid head football coach with a salary of approximately $500.  He was Nebraska's head football coach during the 1893 and 1894 seasons and compiled a 9\u20134\u20131 record.  After starting the 1893 season with a 2\u20132\u20131 record, Crawford's team defeated [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]], 20\u201318, in a match played in near-blizzard conditions and considered the \"first major victory\" in Nebraska history.  Crawford reportedly also played right halfback and kicked the field goals for Nebraska during the 1893 Iowa game; he was identified in the record book as \"Frank.\"  In 1894, Crawford's team defeated Iowa, 36\u20130. The 1895 team finished the season with five consecutive victories for a 7\u20132 record and the school's first ever conference championship.  During Crawford's tenure at Nebraska, [[George Flippin]] played for Crawford and became the first African-American athlete in Nebraska history.<ref name=NEB>{{cite web|title=Frank Crawford Bio|publisher=Huskers.com|url=http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991}}</ref> However, in 1893, Flippin was voted team captain by the team, but this decision was vetoed by Crawford, stating: \"It takes a man with brains to be a captain; all there is to Flippin is brute force.\" Flippin went on to be a well-respected [[physician]] in [[Polk County, Nebraska]] and the first African-American inducted into the Nebraska Football Hall of Fame.<ref>http://journalstar.com/news/local/mckee-george-flippin-physician-and-football-hero/article_6ee2bf06-a58c-5205-84cf-3a09e06f4501.html</ref><ref>http://www.omaha.com/living/nebraskan-publishes-book-on-george-flippin-nu-s-first-black/article_98d7f8fa-5ace-11e4-9900-001a4bcf6878.html</ref>\n\n===Texas===\nIn 1894, the [[University of Texas]] football team suffered its first loss in school history, a 28\u20130 home loss to [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]].  The previous head coach was fired, and a lengthy search was conducted for a replacement.  In October 1895, Texas hired Crawford.  At Texas, he was known as \"Little\" Crawford and reportedly \"taught the Yale system of play and stressed conditioning.\"<ref name=UT>{{cite web|title=Football: Head Coaches |publisher=TexasSports.com |url=http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fb-head-coaches.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119064141/http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fb-head-coaches.html |archivedate=November 19, 2012 }}</ref>  Crawford led the 1895 Longhorns to a perfect 5\u20130 record, as the team outscored its opponents by a combined 96\u20130 margin.  After a Thanksgiving Day victory over San Antonio by a score of 38\u20130, Crawford reportedly left for Mexico to watch bullfights and then returned to his home in Nebraska.<ref name=UT/>  The 1895 season was Crawford's last as a football coach.\n\n==Legal and teaching career==\n[[File:Frank Crawford (1909).png|thumb|right|165px|Crawford as law professor at Creighton, 1909.]]\nIn 1893, Crawford opened a law practice with [[Albert Jefferis]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska]].<ref name=BENT>{{cite web|title=University of Michigan Football Coaches: Mike Murphy and Frank Crawford|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/coaches/crawford.htm}}</ref>  Jefferis was a classmate and teammate with Crawford on the baseball and football teams at the University of Michigan and later served in the [[United States House of Representatives]].  In 1901, Crawford formed a law partnership in Omaha under the name Crawford & Clarke with [[Henry Clarke (baseball)|Henry Teft Clarke, Jr.]], a former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alumni Affairs: Henry T. Clarke, Jr.|publisher=The University of Chicago Magazine|page=116|date=January 1916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLMiAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nCrawford joined the faculty of [[Creighton University]] School of Law in 1906 where he remained until 1913.<ref name=Psi>[https://archive.org/details/twelfthgeneralca00psiurich The twelfth general catalogue of the Psi Upsilon Fraternity], by Psi Upsilon Fraternity, 1917, p. 158.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Corrine Jacox|title=A Century of Creighton University School of Law Faculty Publications, 1904-2004|page=14|date=August 2009|publisher=Creighton University Klutznick Law Library / McGrath North Mullin & Kratz Legal Research Center|url=http://www.creighton.edu/fileadmin/user/law-school/faculty/publications/RetrospectiveFacultyBibliography.pdf}}</ref>  He taught classes in evidence and public service companies.<ref name=TCB>{{cite book|title=The Creighton Brief|publisher=The Students of Creighton College of Law|page=19|date=April 10, 1909|url=https://archive.org/details/creightonbrief00univgoog}}</ref>\n\nFrom the end of [[World War I]] until the outbreak of [[World War II]], Crawford practiced law in France, first in [[Paris, France|Paris]] and later in [[Nice, France|Nice]].<ref name=BENT/>\n\n==Family and death==\nCrawford was married to Hannah Louise McNair, a descendant of four colonial governors. Crawford and his wife moved to France in the mid-1920s and to [[New York City]] in the early 1940s. His wife died in September 1943 at the [[French Hospital (Manhattan)|French Hospital]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite new|title=Mrs. Crawford, Vassar, 1902, Dies|newspaper=Poughkeepsie New Yorker|date=September 29, 1943|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559597/mrs_crawford_vassar_1902_dies/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Louis Crawford Rites Held at Omaha|newspaper=The Lincoln Star|date=September 30, 1943|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559473/mrs_louis_crawford_rites_held_at_omah/}}</ref>\nIn November 1963, Crawford died at a hospital in [[Portland, Maine]] at age 93.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crawford, Michigan Grid Founder, Dies|newspaper=The Sun, Baltimore, Md.|date=November 27, 1963|page=20|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559359/crawford_michigan_grid_founder_dies/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=November 27, 1963|title=Ex Grid Coach Crawford Dies}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan Wolverines]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1891\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1891 college football season|1891]]\n | name         = [[1891 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n | overall      = 4\u20135\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Michigan\n | overall    = 4\u20135\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin Badgers]]\n | conf      = [[Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the Northwest]]\n | startyear = 1892\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1892 college football season|1892]]\n | name         = [[1892 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]\n | overall      = 4\u20133\n | conference   = 2\u20132\n | confstanding = 2nd\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Wisconsin\n | overall    = 4\u20133\n | confrecord = 2\u20132\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Bugeaters]]\n | conf      = [[Western Interstate University Football Association]]\n | startyear = 1893\n | endyear   = 1894\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1893 college football season|1893]]\n | name         = [[1893 Nebraska Bugeaters football team|Nebraska]]\n | overall      = 3\u20132\u20131\n | conference   = 1\u20132\n | confstanding = 3rd\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1894 college football season|1894]]\n | name         = [[1894 Nebraska Bugeaters football team|Nebraska]]\n | overall      = 6\u20132\n | conference   = 2\u20131\n | confstanding = 1st\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship = conference\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Nebraska\n | overall    = 9\u20134\u20131\n | confrecord = 3\u20133\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas Longhorns]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1895\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1895 college football season|1895]]\n | name         = [[1895 Texas Longhorns football team|Texas]]\n | overall      = 5\u20130\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Texas\n | overall    = 5\u20130\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Nebraska Wesleyan Prairie Wolves football|Nebraska Wesleyan]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1896\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship =\n | year         = [[1896 college football season|1896]]\n | name         = Nebraska Wesleyan\n | overall      = 3\u20132\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Nebraska Wesleyan\n | overall    = 3\u20132\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 25\u201314\u20131\n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/coaches/crawford.htm Profile at Bentley Historical Library, University of Michigan Athletics History]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Michigan Wolverines football coach navbox}}\n{{Wisconsin Badgers football coach navbox}}\n{{Baker Wildcats football coach navbox}}\n{{Nebraska Cornhuskers football coach navbox}}\n{{Texas Longhorns football coach navbox}}\n{{Nebraska Wesleyan Prairie Wolves football coach navbox}}\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crawford, Frank}}\n[[Category:1870 births]]\n[[Category:1963 deaths]]\n[[Category:Baker Wildcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines football coaches]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Cornhuskers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Nebraska Wesleyan Prairie Wolves football coaches]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns football coaches]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Badgers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Creighton University faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Colebrook, New Hampshire]]\n[[Category:People from Baldwin City, Kansas]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Frank Crawford\n| image = Frank Crawford.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1870|3|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1963|11|25|1870|3|12}}\n| death_place = [[Portland, Maine]]\n| alma_mater = \n| coach_years1 = 1891\n| coach_team1 = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]]\n| coach_years2 = 1892\n| coach_team2 = [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]]\n| coach_years3 = 1893\u20131894\n| coach_team3 = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]\n| coach_years4 = 1895\n| coach_team4 = [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| coach_years5 = 1896\n| coach_team5 = [[Nebraska Wesleyan Prairie Wolves football|Nebraska Wesleyan]]\n| overall_record = 25\u201314\u20131\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = 1 [[Western Interstate University Football Association|WIUFA]] (1894)\n| awards = \n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Frank Crawford''' (March 12, 1870 \u2013 November 25, 1963) was a [[college football]] coach, lawyer, and law professor.  He attended [[Yale University]] and served as the first head football coach at the [[University of Michigan]] in 1891.  He also coached at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] (1892), [[Baker University]] (1892), the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]] (1893\u20131894), and the [[University of Texas at Austin|University of Texas]] (1895).  He later had a long career as a lawyer in Nebraska and France. He was a professor of law at [[Creighton University School of Law|Creighton College of Law]] from 1906 to 1913.\n\n==Early years==\nCrawford was born in 1870 at [[Colebrook, New Hampshire]].<ref name=TCB/>  He was the son of Francis B. Crawford, a starch manufacturer and state legislator, and Susan J. (Randall) Crawford.<ref>1880 United States Census; Census Place: Colebrook, Coos, New Hampshire; Roll: 762; Family History Film: 1254762; Page: 31A; Enumeration District: 31; Image: 0063.</ref><ref>United States Passport Applications by Frank Crawford dated December 22, 1919 and December 14, 1921 identifies his father as Francis B. Crawford and his date of birth as March 12, 1870 in Colebrook, New Hampshire.</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Genealogical and Family History of the State of New Hampshire, vol. 2|page=930|publisher=Lewis Publishing Co.|year=1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cfoI0UIOCKQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>  He attended preparatory school at [[St. Johnsbury Academy]] in [[St. Johnsbury, Vermont]].<ref name=TCB/>  He enrolled at [[Yale University]], receiving his Bachelor of Arts degree in 1891.  Sources are at odds over whether or not Crawford played football for the [[Yale Bulldogs football]] team.  According to the University of Nebraska web site, Crawford was \"a member of the dominant Yale teams of the mid-1880s.\"<ref name=NEB/>  ''[[The Michigan Daily]]'' also reported that Crawford played football at Yale \"for several years.\"<ref name=BENT/>  However, the University of Michigan web site notes that \"Yale archivists found no evidence that he played varsity football\" and concludes that Crawford \"may have played some football while a Bulldog, but definitely did not win a varsity letter.\"<ref name=BENT/>\n\n==Coaching career==\n\n===Michigan===\nAfter graduating from Yale, Crawford enrolled at the [[University of Michigan School of Law]], receiving his law degree in 1893.  As a first-year law student, Crawford was both the unpaid coach and a substitute player for the [[1891 Michigan Wolverines football team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1891 Football Team|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/fbteam/1891fbt.htm}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1891 Michigan Football Roster|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110703111500/http://141.211.39.65/allroster/FMPro?-DB=allrost.fp5&-Format=fbresult.htm&-SortField=name&-SortOrder=Ascend&year=1891&-max=170&-Find|archivedate=July 3, 2011}}</ref>  He helped lead the team to a 4\u20135 record.  He has been identified by several sources as the first football coach in University of Michigan history.<ref>{{cite news|title=Forum|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 60|year=1954|page=258}}(\"He [Crawford] was the first football coach in University of Michigan history and he was unpaid.\")</ref><ref name=MA08>{{cite news|title=Alumni Meeting in Omaha|publisher=The Michigan Alumnus, Volume 15|date=December 1908|page=116|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZgjiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}(\"Frank Crawford first coach of a Michigan football team and captain of the baseball team\")</ref>  Other sources indicate that Crawford and [[Mike Murphy (trainer and coach)|Mike Murphy]] were the joint head coaches of the 1891 Michigan football team.<ref name=BENT/>  Others state that Murphy relinquished the coaching duties to Crawford midway through the season to allow him to focus on his duties as trainer.<ref name=NEB/>  The ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'' reported in November 1891 that the Michigan team was \"coached systematically\" by Murphy, Crawford, [[Horace Greely Prettyman]] and [[James E. Duffy (American football)|James Duffy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Players From Ann Arbor: A New but Strong Team Which Will Play a Clean Game|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=November 14, 1891}}</ref>\n\nWhile attending Michigan, Crawford also played for the [[Michigan Wolverines baseball]] team in 1892 and 1893.  He led the team with a .976 fielding average in 1892.<ref name=MB/>  Crawford appeared in 17 games at catcher and left field for the Wolverines in 1892 and was among the team's leaders in runs (tied for 2nd with 20), stolen bases (tied for 2nd with 13) and putouts (2nd with 115).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Palladium, Vol XXXV|year=1893|page=180|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sSwiAAAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=crawford#v=onepage&q=crawford&f=false}}</ref> He was also selected as the captain of the 1893 baseball team.<ref name=MB>{{cite book|title=The Michigan Book|pages=[https://archive.org/details/michiganbook01michgoog/page/n160 154]\u2013155|publisher=The Inland Press|year=1898|url=https://archive.org/details/michiganbook01michgoog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan Baseball Captains|date=June 5, 2009|publisher=Mgoblue.com|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060509aac.html|access-date=March 5, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714082426/http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/060509aac.html|archive-date=July 14, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn his history of the University of Michigan, Wilfred Byron Shaw cites Crawford's hiring as a watershed moment in the history of the school's football program: \"A new era in the history of football at Michigan began in 1891, when with a fair schedule and an experienced coach, Frank Crawford (Yale, '91), '93l, the systematic development of a team began ...\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilfred Byron Shaw|title=The University of Michigan|page=[https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu/page/250 250]|year=1920|publisher=Harcourt, Brace, and Howe|url=https://archive.org/details/akr2122.0001.001.umich.edu}}</ref>  Although football had been played at Michigan without a coaching staff since 1879, the [[Associated Press]] noted at the time of Crawford's death that Crawford \"is credited with introducing football at the University of Michigan in 1891.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Founder of Football At Michigan U. Dies|newspaper=Del-Rio News Herald (AP story)|date=November 26, 1963}}</ref>\n\n===Wisconsin===\nIn 1892, he coached at [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison|University of Wisconsin]] and compiled a 4\u20133 record.<ref>{{cite news|title=Frank Crawford |publisher=Sports-Reference.com/College Football |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/frank-crawford-1.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105072909/http://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/frank-crawford-1.html |archivedate=November 5, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1892 Wisconsin Football|publisher=College Football Data Warehouse|url=http://cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=475&year=1892}}</ref>\n\n===Baker===\nIn November 1892, Crawford served as \"a paid coach-captain player\" for the football team at [[Baker University]] at [[Baldwin, Kansas]].<ref name=sears/>  Crawford reportedly \"brought many innovations,\" including the training table, to Baker's football program.<ref name=sears>{{cite news|author=Hal D. Sears|title=The Moral Threat of Intercollegiate Sports: An 1893 Poll of Ten College Presidents, and the End of \"The Champion Football Team of the Great West\"|publisher=Journal of Sport History, Vol. 19, No. 3|date=Winter 1992|page=215|url=http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH1992/JSH1903/jsh1903b.pdf}}</ref>  He led Baker to the Kansas state championship and a 2\u20131 record in \"the triangular league,\" including victories over [[Washburn Ichabods football|Washburn]] (44\u20130) and Kansas (18\u20130).  In December 1892, the ''Leavenworth Times'' reported that Crawford had \"succeeded in instilling sufficient foot ball lore into the western farmers to accomplish the defeat of the University of Kansas team by the Baker eleven last week.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=A Tale Unfolded|newspaper=The Daily World (reprinting article from Leavenworth Times)|date=November 27, 1892|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=wCtdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7VoNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4605,3163149&dq=frank-crawford+%26+baker-university&hl=en}}</ref>  In May 1893, ''The Baker Beacon'' reported: \"The Baker team was ably coached and captained by Frank Crawford who had learned the game at Yale and by the close of the season the team ... was in excellent condition.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Football|date=May 15, 1893|pages=24\u201325|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0iUVAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n===Nebraska===\nIn 1893, Crawford was hired as the head football coach at the [[University of Nebraska\u2013Lincoln|University of Nebraska]].  He was the school's first paid head football coach with a salary of approximately $500.  He was Nebraska's head football coach during the 1893 and 1894 seasons and compiled a 9\u20134\u20131 record.  After starting the 1893 season with a 2\u20132\u20131 record, Crawford's team defeated [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]], 20\u201318, in a match played in near-blizzard conditions and considered the \"first major victory\" in Nebraska history.  Crawford reportedly also played right halfback and kicked the field goals for Nebraska during the 1893 Iowa game; he was identified in the record book as \"Frank.\"  In 1894, Crawford's team defeated Iowa, 36\u20130. The 1895 team finished the season with five consecutive victories for a 7\u20132 record and the school's first ever conference championship.  During Crawford's tenure at Nebraska, [[George Flippin]] played for Crawford and became the first African-American athlete in Nebraska history.<ref name=NEB>{{cite web|title=Frank Crawford Bio|publisher=Huskers.com|url=http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=920991}}</ref> However, in 1893, Flippin was voted team captain by the team, but this decision was vetoed by Crawford, stating: \"It takes a man with brains to be a captain; all there is to Flippin is brute force.\" Flippin went on to be a well-respected [[physician]] in [[Polk County, Nebraska]] and the first African-American inducted into the Nebraska Football Hall of Fame.<ref>http://journalstar.com/news/local/mckee-george-flippin-physician-and-football-hero/article_6ee2bf06-a58c-5205-84cf-3a09e06f4501.html</ref><ref>http://www.omaha.com/living/nebraskan-publishes-book-on-george-flippin-nu-s-first-black/article_98d7f8fa-5ace-11e4-9900-001a4bcf6878.html</ref>\n\n===Texas===\nIn 1894, the [[University of Texas]] football team suffered its first loss in school history, a 28\u20130 home loss to [[Missouri Tigers football|Missouri]].  The previous head coach was fired, and a lengthy search was conducted for a replacement.  In October 1895, Texas hired Crawford.  At Texas, he was known as \"Little\" Crawford and reportedly \"taught the Yale system of play and stressed conditioning.\"<ref name=UT>{{cite web|title=Football: Head Coaches |publisher=TexasSports.com |url=http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fb-head-coaches.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119064141/http://www.texassports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/fb-head-coaches.html |archivedate=November 19, 2012 }}</ref>  Crawford led the 1895 Longhorns to a perfect 5\u20130 record, as the team outscored its opponents by a combined 96\u20130 margin.  After a Thanksgiving Day victory over San Antonio by a score of 38\u20130, Crawford reportedly left for Mexico to watch bullfights and then returned to his home in Nebraska.<ref name=UT/>  The 1895 season was Crawford's last as a football coach.\n\n==Legal and teaching career==\n[[File:Frank Crawford (1909).png|thumb|right|165px|Crawford as law professor at Creighton, 1909.]]\nIn 1893, Crawford opened a law practice with [[Albert Jefferis]] in [[Omaha, Nebraska]].<ref name=BENT>{{cite web|title=University of Michigan Football Coaches: Mike Murphy and Frank Crawford|publisher=University of Michigan, Bentley Historical Library|url=http://bentley.umich.edu/athdept/football/coaches/crawford.htm}}</ref>  Jefferis was a classmate and teammate with Crawford on the baseball and football teams at the University of Michigan and later served in the [[United States House of Representatives]].  In 1901, Crawford formed a law partnership in Omaha under the name Crawford & Clarke with [[Henry Clarke (baseball)|Henry Teft Clarke, Jr.]], a former [[Major League Baseball]] pitcher.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alumni Affairs: Henry T. Clarke, Jr.|publisher=The University of Chicago Magazine|page=116|date=January 1916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rLMiAQAAIAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\nCrawford joined the faculty of [[Creighton University]] School of Law in 1906 where he remained until 1913.<ref name=Psi>[https://archive.org/details/twelfthgeneralca00psiurich The twelfth general catalogue of the Psi Upsilon Fraternity], by Psi Upsilon Fraternity, 1917, p. 158.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Corrine Jacox|title=A Century of Creighton University School of Law Faculty Publications, 1904-2004|page=14|date=August 2009|publisher=Creighton University Klutznick Law Library / McGrath North Mullin & Kratz Legal Research Center|url=http://www.creighton.edu/fileadmin/user/law-school/faculty/publications/RetrospectiveFacultyBibliography.pdf}}</ref>  He taught classes in evidence and public service companies.<ref name=TCB>{{cite book|title=The Creighton Brief|publisher=The Students of Creighton College of Law|page=19|date=April 10, 1909|url=https://archive.org/details/creightonbrief00univgoog}}</ref>\n\nFrom the end of [[World War I]] until the outbreak of [[World War II]], Crawford practiced law in France, first in [[Paris, France|Paris]] and later in [[Nice, France|Nice]].<ref name=BENT/>\n\n==Family and death==\nCrawford was married to Hannah Louise McNair, a descendant of four colonial governors. Crawford and his wife moved to France in the mid-1920s and to [[New York City]] in the early 1940s. His wife died in September 1943 at the [[French Hospital (Manhattan)|French Hospital]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite new|title=Mrs. Crawford, Vassar, 1902, Dies|newspaper=Poughkeepsie New Yorker|date=September 29, 1943|page=2|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559597/mrs_crawford_vassar_1902_dies/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mrs. Louis Crawford Rites Held at Omaha|newspaper=The Lincoln Star|date=September 30, 1943|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559473/mrs_louis_crawford_rites_held_at_omah/}}</ref>\nIn November 1963, Crawford died at a hospital in [[Portland, Maine]] at age 93.<ref>{{cite news|title=Crawford, Michigan Grid Founder, Dies|newspaper=The Sun, Baltimore, Md.|date=November 27, 1963|page=20|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8559359/crawford_michigan_grid_founder_dies/}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=November 27, 1963|title=Ex Grid Coach Crawford Dies}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan Wolverines]]\n | conf      = Independent\n | startyear = 1891\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1891 college football season|1891]]\n | name         = [[1891 Michigan Wolverines football team|Michigan]]\n | overall      = 4\u20135\n | conference   =\n | confstanding =\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Michigan\n | overall    = 4\u20135\n | confrecord =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin Badgers]]\n | conf      = [[Intercollegiate Athletic Association of the Northwest]]\n | startyear = 1892\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | year         = [[1892 college football season|1892]]\n | name         = [[1892 Wisconsin Badgers football team|Wisconsin]]\n | overall      = 4\u20133\n | conference   = 2\u20132\n | confstanding = 2nd\n | bowlname     =\n | bowloutcome  =\n | bcsbowl      =\n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n | championship =\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Wisconsin\n | overall    = 4\u20133\n | confrecord = 2\u20132\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska Bugeaters]]\n | conf      = [[Western Interstate University Football Association]]\n | startyear = 1893\n | endyear  